english:
  title: Three Discourses on Direct Understanding
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Can heaven be questioned? The Songs of Chu answered this already. Through Han to Tang, Liu Zihou labored unto death to respond to it. Dong Zhongshu said, "The great source of the Way springs from heaven." Thus one awakens as from sleep, grows clear as from intoxication. Yet still he spoke of heaven as that azure dome above, not perceiving that human morality and the nature of things flow from this source, that the whole is itself heaven. Only when one finally says, "Heaven is principle itself," does man begin to know that nothing in human affairs lies outside of heaven.

    Nature dwells in both man and thing. We name them man and thing by outward form—this is mere appearance. When we seek the reason and distinguish their essence, the nature in man is nature, and the nature in thing is also nature. One nature means one heaven—why doubt this? When a subject serves, he is called subject; when a lord commands, he is called lord. Born in Chu, summoned to Jin—this cannot be divided by state. Faithless to Sui, loyal to Tang—this cannot be divided by person. When harmony prevails, fish glide through waters and birds soar through clouds. When discord reigns, though a master play the zither, Qi will not hear it—so lord and subject meet or part by some mysterious destiny. In extremity, they regard each other as enemies, as beasts: their situation cannot hold, their hearts cannot commune. Alas, the danger! Should an ambitious villain stir in such a breach, the great work is lost. Alas, the danger!

    The mind's power is vast—it orders heaven and earth with strength to spare, no speck escapes its reach. Heaven and earth themselves cannot contain its measure. The ancients who wielded it well were the Two Emperors and Three Kings. Those who preserved it well were Confucius, Yan Hui, Zisi, and Mencius. They enacted it through statecraft, expressed it through writing, and thus its application became manifest. What lies hidden and unseen is not in some dim and soundless void, but shines bright as sun and moon, flourishes potent as spirits and ghosts—seek it nowhere but in the span of your own heart.

    When one hears noble words and sees noble deeds, what surges forth is the heart's awakening sprout. To grasp this sprout and never lose it—this is reverence and righteousness, nothing more. Hold fast, hold fast!
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Songs of Chu (楚辭): A collection of poems from the Warring States period, attributed to Qu Yuan and his successors. Here it refers specifically to Qu Yuan''s ''Questions of Heaven'' (天問), which famously begins by questioning the nature of heaven.'
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Two Emperors' typically refer to mythical sage rulers; the 'Three Kings' are the legendary rulers of early Chinese civilization. Lee Saek uses these figures to represent the ideal application of mind and principle through governance.
  - key: ''
    value: The zither (瑟) reference alludes to the Analects, where Confucius remarks that beautiful music played on a zither finds no appreciation in the state of Qi—a metaphor for how virtue depends on the receptivity of one's environment.
